Gemini said
If you're running Arch Linux and need to recover the password for the network you are currently using, you can find it stored in your network configuration files. On most Arch setups, this is handled by NetworkManager.

Since these files contain sensitive security credentials, you will need sudo privileges to view them.

Method 1: Using the Command Line (NetworkManager)
NetworkManager stores connection profiles in /etc/NetworkManager/system-connections/. Each Wi-Fi network has its own file.

List your saved connections to find the exact name (SSID):
nmcli connection show

Display the password for your specific network (replace YourWiFiName with the actual SSID):
sudo nmcli -s device wifi show-password
Note: The -s flag asks the secret agent for the password.

Alternatively, you can read the configuration file directly:
sudo cat /etc/NetworkManager/system-connections/YourWiFiName.nmconnection

Look for the line under [wifi-security] that starts with psk=.

Method 2: If you use iwd (iNet wireless daemon)
If you’ve ditched NetworkManager for iwd, the profiles are stored in a different location:

sudo cat /var/lib/iwd/YourWiFiName.psk

The password will be listed next to Passphrase=.

Method 3: The GUI Way (If using KDE or GNOME)
If you are using a desktop environment, you don't even need the terminal:

GNOME: Go to Settings > Wi-Fi, click the gear icon next to your network, and look under the Security tab. Check "Show password."

KDE Plasma: Click the network icon in your tray, select the connection, click Configure, go to the Wi-Fi Security tab, and click the eye icon in the password field.

Quick Security Tip: Since Arch doesn't "hide" these passwords from anyone with root access, it's a good reminder that if someone gains physical access to your machine or your root password, they have your Wi-Fi keys too.

